03873nam a22006015i 9780226507675DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017011913  a9780226507675  a(DE-B1597)523699  a(OCoLC)1011673799  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBL51b.L477 2017 4aBL51b.L477 2018 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a2102231 aLevene, Nancy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPowers of Distinction :bOn Religion and Modernity /cNancy Levene. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. The Principle of Modernity -- t2. A History of Religion -- t3. Artificial Populations -- t4. The Collective -- t5. Images of Truth from Anselm to Badiou -- t6. The Radical Enlightenment of Spinoza and Kant -- t7. Modernity as Ground Zero -- t8. Of Gods, Laws, Rabbis, and Ends -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this major new work, philosopher of religion Nancy Levene examines the elemental character of religion and modernity. Deep in their operating systems, she argues, are dualisms of opposition and identity that cannot be reconciled with the forms of life they ostensibly support. These dualisms are dead ends, but they conceal a richer position—another kind of dualism constitutive of mutual relation. This dualism is difficult to distinguish and its concept of relation difficult to commit to. It risks contention and even violence. But it is also the indispensable support for modernity’s most innovative ideals: democracy, criticism, and interpretation. In readings from Abraham to the present, Levene recovers this richer dualism in its difference from the alternatives—other dualisms, nondualism, multiplication. From Abraham we get the biblical call to give up tribal belonging for a promised land of covenantal relation. Yet modernity, inclusive of this call, is also the principle that critiques the promise when it divides self from other, us from them. Drawing on a long tradition of thinkers and scholars even as she breaks new ground, Levene offers here nothing less than a new way of understanding modernity as an ethical claim about our world, a philosophy of the powers of distinction to include rather than to divide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aModernism (Christian theology) 0aModernism (Christian theology). 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aAbraham.  ademocracy.  adistinction.  adualism.  amodernity.  areligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022650736140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226507675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226507675/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles